{
  "name": "kiro-recall: Session Capture",
  "version": "2.1.0",
  "description": "Fires at session end. Reviews session context, generates a structured session summary, and writes it to 00-inbox/ via mcpvault.",
  "when": {
    "type": "agentStop"
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "You are running the kiro-recall session capture hook. This hook fires at session end. Your job is to review the session, generate a structured session summary, and write it to the local vault inbox.\n\n## Preamble — Check vault availability\n\nBefore doing anything else, confirm that the mcpvault MCP server is available. Attempt a lightweight mcpvault operation (for example, listing the contents of `00-inbox/`).\n\nIf mcpvault responds successfully, proceed to Step 1.\n\nIf mcpvault is unavailable, not connected, or returns a connection error, output the following message and stop immediately. Do not proceed to any further steps.\n\n> Vault sync skipped this time. The vault connection wasn't available, but no worries — your session completed just fine. The note will be captured next time the hook fires successfully.\n\nDo not output any stack traces, exception details, or internal error messages. Just the friendly message above, then stop.\n\n## Step 1 — Gather session context\n\nInspect the conversation history and any spec files worked on during the session. Gather context about what was built, decided, or learned.\n\nLook for:\n- Code changes, new files, or features implemented\n- Design decisions or trade-offs discussed\n- New knowledge, patterns, or insights discovered\n- Spec tasks completed or progressed\n\n### Meaningful work threshold\n\nBefore proceeding, apply this threshold. A session qualifies as meaningful only if it meets at least ONE of the following criteria:\n\n1. **Files changed** — at least one file was created, edited, or deleted during the session\n2. **Substantive decisions** — at least one architectural, design, or implementation decision was made and discussed (not just acknowledged with a one-word reply)\n3. **Spec or task progress** — at least one spec task was completed, or a requirements/design/tasks document was written or significantly updated\n4. **Multi-turn technical discussion** — the session contained at least 4 exchanges (user + agent turns) focused on a technical problem, not just setup or configuration Q&A\n5. **Knowledge capture** — something was explicitly learned or discovered that would be worth recalling in a future session\n\nSessions that do NOT qualify (output the stop message and halt):\n- Short Q&A exchanges of 1–3 turns with no file changes\n- Single-word or single-sentence confirmations (e.g. \"GitHub\", \"Keep defaults\", \"Yes\", \"Confirmed\")\n- Setup wizard steps where the user is just answering configuration questions\n- Sessions where the only output was a question presented to the user with no answer yet\n- Greetings, meta-questions about the tool, or sessions with no workspace context\n\nIf the session does NOT meet the threshold, output this message exactly and stop — do not proceed further:\n\n> Nothing substantial to capture from this session.\n\nIf the session meets the threshold, carry the gathered context forward to Step 2.\n\n## Step 2 — Resolve project name\n\nDetermine the project name for this capture using the same relevance detection logic as the session-start and auto-vault-sync hooks. The resolution follows a priority chain: primary signal, then secondary signal, then fallback.\n\n### Extract Workspace Name\n\nExtract the Workspace Name: take the final path segment of the current workspace root folder path. For example, from `C:\\Dev\\kiro-recall` the Workspace Name is `kiro-recall`.\n\n### Check for Generic Name\n\nCompare the Workspace Name (case-insensitive) against this fixed list:\n\n`src`, `dev`, `project`, `app`, `code`, `workspace`, `repo`, `main`, `test`, `build`, `website`, `frontend`, `backend`, `api`, `server`, `client`, `lib`, `library`, `core`, `base`\n\nIf the Workspace Name matches any entry in this list, skip the Primary Signal entirely and proceed directly to the Secondary Signal.\n\n### Primary Signal\n\nWorkspace Name is not generic. Use mcpvault to list the contents of `01-projects/` in the vault.\n\nSearch for a file or subfolder whose name case-insensitively matches the Workspace Name.\n\nIf a match is found, use that entry as the resolved project name. Stop — do not evaluate further signals.\n\nIf no match is found, proceed to the Secondary Signal.\n\n### Secondary Signal\n\nInspect the paths of all files currently open in the workspace. For each open file path, split the path into its individual segments (folder and file names). Check whether any segment case-insensitively matches a subfolder name inside `01-projects/` in the vault. Use the first such match as the resolved project name.\n\nIf no open-file match is found, attempt to read the files inside `.kiro/steering/` in the current workspace. If any steering file contains a `project` field (e.g. a line like `project: my-project` or a YAML/markdown frontmatter field named `project`), use that value as a candidate project name — but only if it case-insensitively matches a subfolder name in `01-projects/`.\n\nIf a match is found via either method, use it as the resolved project name. Stop — do not evaluate the fallback.\n\n### Fallback\n\nNeither primary nor secondary signal resolved a project name. Use `unknown` as the resolved project name.\n\nCarry the resolved project name forward to subsequent steps.\n\n## Step 3 — Build Session Summary\n\nConstruct the Session Summary as a markdown block. Start with a horizontal rule (`---`) followed by a blank line, then the seven `##` headings in this exact order:\n\n```\n---\n\n## Date\nYYYY-MM-DD\n\n## Project\n{resolved project name}\n\n## Session-type\nagentStop\n\n## What was built\n{1-3 sentences describing concrete artifacts, features, or code}\n\n## What was decided\n{1-3 sentences describing design decisions, trade-offs, or direction changes}\n\n## What was learned\n{1-3 sentences describing new knowledge, insights, or patterns}\n\n## Article candidate topics\n- {concrete article angle grounded in session work}\n- {another topic, if applicable}\n```\n\nRules:\n- Use today's date in ISO 8601 format (YYYY-MM-DD) for the Date field.\n- The Project field uses the name resolved in Step 2.\n- The Session-type field is always `agentStop` for this hook.\n- \"What was built\" should be 1-3 sentences describing concrete artifacts, features, or code produced during the session.\n- \"What was decided\" should be 1-3 sentences describing design decisions, trade-offs chosen, or direction changes made during the session.\n- \"What was learned\" should be 1-3 sentences describing new knowledge, insights, or patterns discovered during the session.\n- \"Article candidate topics\" should be a bulleted list of 1-3 concrete article angles grounded in specific session work. Each item starts with `- `. Do not generate generic topics like \"Getting Started with AWS\" — every topic must be tied to something that actually happened in this session.\n- When a narrative field (What was built, What was decided, What was learned) has no relevant content from the session, use \"Nothing notable this session.\" as the placeholder text for that field. Do not omit the heading.\n- All seven headings must appear in the summary, in the order shown above. No headings may be omitted, reordered, or renamed.\n\nCarry the completed Session Summary forward to Step 4.\n\n## Step 4 — Derive filename\n\nConstruct the filename for the Session Summary using this format:\n\n```\nYYYY-MM-DD-{project}-session-capture.md\n```\n\nWhere:\n- `YYYY-MM-DD` is today's date (same date used in the Session Summary).\n- `{project}` is the resolved project name from Step 2.\n\nThe suffix is always `session-capture` — this is a fixed suffix, not a task slug. Multiple sessions for the same project on the same day are appended to the same file, separated by `---` horizontal rules.\n\nExamples:\n- `2025-07-18-kiro-recall-session-capture.md`\n- `2025-07-18-unknown-session-capture.md`\n\nCarry the derived filename forward to Step 5.\n\n## Step 5 — Write to vault\n\nUse mcpvault to write the Session Summary (from Step 3) to `00-inbox/{filename}` in the vault.\n\nFirst, check whether the file already exists by attempting to read it. If the file exists, use mcpvault's append mode to add the Session Summary to the end of the existing file. If the file does not exist, use mcpvault's overwrite mode to create it (but omit the leading `---` separator since this is the first entry).\n\nThis ensures multiple sessions for the same project on the same day accumulate in a single file rather than overwriting each other.\n\nIf the write succeeds, proceed to Step 6.\n\nIf the write fails for any reason, display the following message:\n\n> Couldn't save your session summary to the vault — here's what was captured so you don't lose it:\n\nImmediately follow that message with the full Session Summary content inside a markdown code block, so the user can copy and save it manually.\n\nDo NOT retry the write. Do NOT surface stack traces, exception messages, or internal file paths. Output only the warm failure message and the summary content, then stop.\n\n## Step 6 — Report outcome\n\nThe vault write succeeded. Output a short success message:\n\n> Session captured to vault.\n\nNo additional output needed.\n\n## Error Output Rules\n\nThese rules apply to every failure path in this hook, no exceptions.\n\n1. Never include stack traces, exception class names, or absolute file system paths in any output. If something fails, the user sees a short, friendly message — not internals.\n2. The Session Summary content is displayed in a markdown code block ONLY when the vault write fails. When the write succeeds, no code block is needed.\n3. All failure messages should feel warm and conversational — the same tone as the rest of the kiro-recall hooks. Think helpful teammate, not error log."
  }
}